{"id":"2210.06011","submitter":"Bin Shi","authors":"Bin Shi, Dehai Luo, Wenqi Zhang","title":"Optimal Initial Disturbance of Atmospheric Blocking: A Barotropic View","comments":"24 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph nlin.CD","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we investigate the optimal initial disturbance of the blocking\nevent in the equivalent barotropic atmosphere by use of the nonlinear\nmultiscale interaction (NMI) model. The soliton wave-like spatial distribution\nof the optimal initial disturbance, centered around the zonal location and\nhighly related to the slowly varying amplitude distribution of preexisting\nsynoptic-scale eddies, is obtained by the standard conditional nonlinear\noptimal perturbation (CNOP) method. By demonstrating how the constraint\ndomain's size affects the optimal initial disturbance in the spatial\ndistribution and the nonlinear time evolution behavior, we find that the\nnonlinear time evolution behavior of the blocking is very sensitive to the\noptimal initial disturbance. When the weakening of the background westerly wind\nfavors the maintenance of the atmospheric blocking, the error in the initial\nblocking will lead to a strong nonlinear error growth of blocking evolution in\nthis case. This makes the prediction of long-lived atmospheric blocking and\nassociated severe extreme weather events more difficult. Finally, we provide a\ntheoretical explanation for the cause of why the optimal initial disturbance\nchanges with the background westerly wind in such a way, based on the theory of\nthe NMI model, that the dispersive effect is proportional to the meridional\npotential vorticity gradient ($PV_y$) and the nonlinear effect is inversely\nproportional to $PV_y$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Oct 2022 08:29:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 3 Feb 2023 06:14:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-06"