{"id":"2210.06039","submitter":"Rahul Deshpande","authors":"Rahul Deshpande, Charitha M. de Silva and Ivan Marusic","title":"Evidence that superstructures are concatenations of self-similar\n  coherent motions in high $Re_{\\tau}$ boundary layers","comments":"Preprint submitted to the Journal of Fluid Mechanics after first\n  revision, with 25 pages, 15 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  We present evidence suggesting that the superstructures in turbulent boundary\nlayers are concatenations of smaller, geometrically self-similar coherent\nmotions. The evidence comes from identifying and analyzing instantaneous\nsuperstructures from large-scale particle image velocimetry datasets acquired\nat high Reynolds numbers, capable of capturing streamwise elongated motions\nextending up to 12 times the boundary layer thickness. Given the challenge in\nidentifying the constituent motions of the superstructures based on streamwise\nvelocity signatures, a new approach is adopted that investigates the\nwall-normal velocity fluctuations within these very long motions, which reveals\nthe constituent motions unambiguously. The conditional streamwise energy\nspectra of the wall-normal fluctuations, corresponding exclusively to the\nsuperstructure region, are found to exhibit the well-known\ndistance-from-the-wall scaling in the intermediate scale range. This indicates\ngeometrically self-similar motions co-exist within the superstructure region.\nThe same spectra also exhibit a unique energy enhancement at the outer scales.\nSince the wall-normal momentum-carrying eddies do not conform with these scales\nin a physical sense, the large-scale energy enhancement is shown to be\nassociated with spatially clustered/packed organization of self-similar motions\nover extended streamwise distances (i.e. concatenation), which plausibly leads\nto the appearance of superstructures. The association of the superstructures\nwith the self-similar motions is further reinforced by computing conditionally\naveraged two-point correlations, representing the vertical coherence of the\nconstituent motions, which are found to match with the mean correlations. The\nfindings support the prospect for modelling these dynamically significant\nmotions via data-driven coherent structure-based models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Oct 2022 09:15:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 16 Apr 2023 00:54:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-18"}
